    "When the complexity distribution of tasks is bounded, full automation is reached in nite time and leads to a collapse in wages, no matter what savings behavior the representative agent pursues.",
    "For unbounded complexity distributions of tasks, we show that if the tail of remaining tasks is suciently thick, wages will rise forever.",
    "By contrast, if the tail of unautomated tasks is too thin, wages will eventually collapse.",
    "Next, we simulate a range of scenarios to illustrate our ndings numerically.",
    "(Figure 8 on page 24 shows the main results.)"
